{"File":"/home/ruggedcoder/softwares/fresh/anydb_flutter/.chat_context/transcript.jsonl","LineNumber":2277,"LineContent":"{\"step_index\":2308,\"source\":\"MODEL\",\"type\":\"SEARCH_WEB\",\"status\":\"DONE\",\"created_at\":\"2026-05-28T09:30:22Z\",\"content\":\"Created At: 2026-05-28T09:30:22Z\\nCompleted At: 2026-05-28T09:30:28Z\\nThe search for \\\"flutter google_sign_in web login not working error\\\" returned the following summary:\\nTo resolve Google Sign-In issues in your Flutter web application, follow this troubleshooting guide focusing on the most common points of failure.\\n\\n### 1. Essential Configuration Checklist\\n*   **Web Client ID:** Ensure you are using the **Web Application** Client ID generated in the [Google Cloud Console](https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/credentials). Do not use Android or iOS Client IDs for the web.\\n*   **Authorized Domains:** In the Google Cloud Console (under your OAuth 2.0 Client ID settings), verify that your domain (e.g., `https://your-domain.com` or `http://localhost:5000`) is explicitly added to the **Authorized JavaScript origins**.\\n*   **Meta Tag Placement:** Ensure the client ID meta tag is placed inside the `\u003chead\u003e` section of your `web/index.html` file, not the `\u003cbody\u003e`.\\n    ```html\\n    \u003chead\u003e\\n      ...\\n      \u003cmeta name=\\\"google-signin-client_id\\\" content=\\\"YOUR_WEB_CLIENT_ID.apps.googleusercontent.com\\\"\u003e\\n    \u003c/head\u003e\\n    ```\\n\\n### 2. Common Fixes for Development (Localhost)\\n*   **Fixed Port:** Google Sign-In often fails if the port changes. Force your development environment to use a specific port so it matches your authorized origin:\\n    ```bash\\n    flutter run -d chrome --web-hostname localhost --web-port 5000\\n    ```\\n    *If using VS Code, you can add this to your `.vscode/launch.json` file in the `args` section for your run configuration.*\\n\\n### 3. Implementation Best Practices\\n*   **Initialization:** In newer versions of the `google_sign_in` package (7.0+), it is recommended to explicitly initialize the instance.\\n    ```dart\\n    final GoogleSignIn _googleSignIn = GoogleSignIn(\\n      clientId: 'YOUR_WEB_CLIENT_ID.apps.googleusercontent.com',\\n      scopes: ['email', 'profile'],\\n    );\\n    ```\\n*   **Platform Specifics:** If you are using the same codebase for mobile and web, use conditional imports or check `kIsWeb` to pass the `clientId` only when running on the web.\\n\\n### 4. Debugging \u0026 Common Errors\\n*   **\\\"Access Blocked: Authorization Error\\\" / \\\"Invalid Scope\\\":** This usually means your OAuth consent screen is not configured correctly or has not been published/verified. Ensure you have added your email as a test user if the app is still in \\\"Testing\\\" mode in the Google Cloud Console.\\n*   **\\\"This browser or app may not be secure\\\":** This often happens on `localhost`. Ensure you are using `http://localhost:5000` (or whichever port you whitelisted) and that it exactly matches the Authorized JavaScript origin in your Cloud Console.\\n*   **Empty/Null Responses:** If you are using Firebase, ensure that \\\"Google\\\" is enabled as a sign-in method in the Firebase Authentication console.\\n\\n### Summary of Troubleshooting Steps\\n1.  **Check Console Errors:** Open Chrome DevTools (F12) and check the \\\"Console\\\" tab for specific error messages (e.g., 400 Bad Request, invalid_origin).\\n2.  **Verify Console Settings:** Double-check the Authorized JavaScript origins in the Google Cloud Console.\\n3.  **Clean \u0026 Rebuild:** Sometimes cached configurations cause issues. Run `flutter clean` and then rebuild the web app.\"}"}
